\begin_layout Standard
MultiGWAS adds distinctive marks to both plots to identify different types
 of SNPs: (a) In the Manhattan plots, the significant SNPs are above a red
 line and the best-ranked SNPs are above a blue line.
 In addition, 
\color blue
SNPS shared between packages are colored green
\color inherit
 (See Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Table-Shared-SNPs"

\end_inset

.b).
 (b) In the QQ plots, a red diagonal line indicates the expected distribution
 under the null hypothesis of no association of SNPs with the phenotype,
 both distributions should coincide, and most SNPs should lie on the diagonal
 line.
 
\color blue
Deviations for a large number of SNPs may reflect inflated 
\emph on
p-values 
\emph default
due to population structure or cryptic relatedness.
 But, it is also expected that few SNPs deviate from the diagonal for a
 truly polygenetic trait 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
