\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Itemize
Gaye2017:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
In genetic association studies the underlying genetic model of inheritance
 of the genetic determinant of a trait is not always known with certainty
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In genetic association studies, it is common practice to assume an additive
 model when the model of the genetic determinant of interest is unknown
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Up to date, there is often no concrete evidence of the genetic mode of inheritan
ce in the studies of complex disease genes.
 Most studies test multiple genetic models to explore the biological rationale
 behind the preference of these genetic models
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Moreover, GWASpoly (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Rosyara2016"

\end_inset

) offers models for different types of polyploid gene action 
\color blue
including
\color inherit
 general, additive, simplex dominant, and duplex dominant.
 On the other hand, TASSEL (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bradbury2007"

\end_inset

) also models different types of gene action for diploids 
\color blue
including
\color inherit
 general, additive, and dominant.
 
\color blue
We propose an automatic selection of the gene action model for both tools
 based on a balance between three criteria: the inflation factor, the replicabil
ity of identified SNPs and the significance of identified SNPs.
 
\color inherit
We inform the user of the selected model based on the automatic strategy;
 we consider this information helps to understand the gene action model
 for the trait of interest.
 Even though the main focus is on the resultant SNPs, the model has assumptions
 that reflect the gene actions for a specific phenotype.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%PAULA: ventaja de integrar - pvalores inflados de shesis  (Balance entre
 sensitividad y especificidad al integrar)
\end_layout

\end_inset

Replicability is a strategy to assess results derived from different methods.
 MultiGWAS integrates results to check for replicability in the results
 from different software.
 By combining results, we can compare the outputs and look for coincidences.
 Some software are more sensible, and others are more specific, but the
 integration allows MultiGWAS to balance specificity and sensitivity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We provide the user with different graphic outputs to help to interpret
 the results.
 We report the SNP profile for the SNPs identified by more than one software.
 The SNP profile gives the researcher visual feedback from the SNP.
 We previously check for significative SNPs based on the 
\emph on
p-value
\emph default
; however, it is essential to go back to the data and check if the SNP is
 a real association between the genotype and phenotype.
 For this purpose, we designed the SNP profile.
\end_layout

